My reasoning is that it is once a day so battery usage should be minimal even on early devices, and for the bulk of modern versions the system will manage it even better, while hopefully avoiding more possible error reports where users see lots of skew. You logged a separate issue about the reminder popping up right as you set it - I didn't comment on that simply because I was able to reproduce it so it was valid and should stay open. This one looks fine though currently, and while that would normally argue for no change, I still like the idea of moving from setInexactRepeating to setRepeating. My reasoning is that it is once a day so battery usage should be minimal even on early devices, and for the bulk of modern versions the system will manage it even better, while hopefully avoiding more possible error reports where users see lots of skew. This one looks fine though currently, and while that would normally argue for no change, I still like the idea of moving from setInexactRepeating to setRepeating. My reasoning is that it is once a day so battery usage should be minimal even on early devices, and for the bulk of modern versions the system will manage it even better, while hopefully avoiding more possible error reports where users see lots of skew.     "body": "Interesting - this is what I saw as well. You logged a separate issue about the reminder popping up right as you set it - I didn't comment on that simply because I was able to reproduce it so it was valid and should stay open. This one looks fine though currently, and while that would normally argue for no change, I still like the idea of moving from setInexactRepeating to setRepeating. My reasoning is that it is once a day so battery usage should be minimal even on early devices, and for the bulk of modern versions the system will manage it even better, while hopefully avoiding more possible error reports where users see lots of skew. My reasoning is that it is once a day so battery usage should be minimal even on early devices, and for the bulk of modern versions the system will manage it even better, while hopefully avoiding more possible error reports where users see lots of skew. This one looks fine though currently, and while that would normally argue for no change, I still like the idea of moving from setInexactRepeating to setRepeating. My reasoning is that it is once a day so battery usage should be minimal even on early devices, and for the bulk of modern versions the system will manage it even better, while hopefully avoiding more possible error reports where users see lots of skew. My reasoning is that it is once a day so battery usage should be minimal even on early devices, and for the bulk of modern versions the system will manage it even better, while hopefully avoiding more possible error reports where users see lots of skew.     "body": "Interesting - this is what I saw as well. You logged a separate issue about the reminder popping up right as you set it - I didn't comment on that simply because I was able to reproduce it so it was valid and should stay open. This one looks fine though currently, and while that would normally argue for no change, I still like the idea of moving from setInexactRepeating to setRepeating. My reasoning is that it is once a day so battery usage should be minimal even on early devices, and for the bulk of modern versions the system will manage it even better, while hopefully avoiding more possible error reports where users see lots of skew. I'm okay either way though really - merge or drop works for me :-)",

You logged a separate issue about the reminder popping up right as you set it - I didn't comment on that simply because I was able to reproduce it so it was valid and should stay open. This one looks fine though currently, and while that would normally argue for no change, I still like the idea of moving from setInexactRepeating to setRepeating. My reasoning is that it is once a day so battery usage should be minimal even on early devices, and for the bulk of modern versions the system will manage it even better, while hopefully avoiding more possible error reports where users see lots of skew. I'm okay either way though really - merge or drop works for me :-)",

I haven't gotten my Android API 15 / 4.0.3 emulator to work with AnkiDroid successfully yet so I can't go back in time that far.\r\n\r\nIt may be that in all the notifications / wakeup battery optimization work they did in API 19 (and later versions) they made even setInexactRepeating work pretty well but on <= API 19 (which includes Android 4.3, which was API 18) it isn't good enough. We are supporting API >=15 so if you can reproduce on your old device then we know we can test this.\r\n\r\nAre you able to build the app from source so you can test with the change in place, assuming you can reproduce the issue? If not, I could post a build of this pull request for you so you can see if it fixes it. Or maybe I can get a 4.3 emulator to work and I can try it with the change myself, if I know that version shows the problem sometimes\r\n\r\nThanks for the help investigating this",

This one looks fine though currently, and while that would normally argue for no change, I still like the idea of moving from setInexactRepeating to setRepeating. My reasoning is that it is once a day so battery usage should be minimal even on early devices, and for the bulk of modern versions the system will manage it even better, while hopefully avoiding more possible error reports where users see lots of skew. This one looks fine though currently, and while that would normally argue for no change, I still like the idea of moving from setInexactRepeating to setRepeating. My reasoning is that it is once a day so battery usage should be minimal even on early devices, and for the bulk of modern versions the system will manage it even better, while hopefully avoiding more possible error reports where users see lots of skew.     "body": "Interesting - this is what I saw as well. You logged a separate issue about the reminder popping up right as you set it - I didn't comment on that simply because I was able to reproduce it so it was valid and should stay open. This one looks fine though currently, and while that would normally argue for no change, I still like the idea of moving from setInexactRepeating to setRepeating. My reasoning is that it is once a day so battery usage should be minimal even on early devices, and for the bulk of modern versions the system will manage it even better, while hopefully avoiding more possible error reports where users see lots of skew. I'm okay either way though really - merge or drop works for me :-)",

This one looks fine though currently, and while that would normally argue for no change, I still like the idea of moving from setInexactRepeating to setRepeating. My reasoning is that it is once a day so battery usage should be minimal even on early devices, and for the bulk of modern versions the system will manage it even better, while hopefully avoiding more possible error reports where users see lots of skew. My reasoning is that it is once a day so battery usage should be minimal even on early devices, and for the bulk of modern versions the system will manage it even better, while hopefully avoiding more possible error reports where users see lots of skew. This one looks fine though currently, and while that would normally argue for no change, I still like the idea of moving from setInexactRepeating to setRepeating. My reasoning is that it is once a day so battery usage should be minimal even on early devices, and for the bulk of modern versions the system will manage it even better, while hopefully avoiding more possible error reports where users see lots of skew. You logged a separate issue about the reminder popping up right as you set it - I didn't comment on that simply because I was able to reproduce it so it was valid and should stay open. This one looks fine though currently, and while that would normally argue for no change, I still like the idea of moving from setInexactRepeating to setRepeating. My reasoning is that it is once a day so battery usage should be minimal even on early devices, and for the bulk of modern versions the system will manage it even better, while hopefully avoiding more possible error reports where users see lots of skew. This one looks fine though currently, and while that would normally argue for no change, I still like the idea of moving from setInexactRepeating to setRepeating. My reasoning is that it is once a day so battery usage should be minimal even on early devices, and for the bulk of modern versions the system will manage it even better, while hopefully avoiding more possible error reports where users see lots of skew.     "body": "Interesting - this is what I saw as well. You logged a separate issue about the reminder popping up right as you set it - I didn't comment on that simply because I was able to reproduce it so it was valid and should stay open. This one looks fine though currently, and while that would normally argue for no change, I still like the idea of moving from setInexactRepeating to setRepeating. My reasoning is that it is once a day so battery usage should be minimal even on early devices, and for the bulk of modern versions the system will manage it even better, while hopefully avoiding more possible error reports where users see lots of skew. My reasoning is that it is once a day so battery usage should be minimal even on early devices, and for the bulk of modern versions the system will manage it even better, while hopefully avoiding more possible error reports where users see lots of skew. This one looks fine though currently, and while that would normally argue for no change, I still like the idea of moving from setInexactRepeating to setRepeating. My reasoning is that it is once a day so battery usage should be minimal even on early devices, and for the bulk of modern versions the system will manage it even better, while hopefully avoiding more possible error reports where users see lots of skew.
